Exploratory Factor Analysis: Satisfaction Of Self

Data loaging + Packages

library(EFA.dimensions)
library(dplyr)
library(psych)
library(sjPlot)
data(data_RSE)
dataset <- data.frame(data_RSE)

Deleting NA variables + Distribution

dataset <- filter(dataset, Q1 > 0, Q2 > 0, Q3 > 0, Q4 > 0, Q5 > 0, Q6 > 0, Q7 > 0, Q8 > 0, Q9 > 0, Q10 > 0)
hist(dataset$Q1)

hist(dataset$Q2)

hist(dataset$Q3)

hist(dataset$Q4)

hist(dataset$Q5)

hist(dataset$Q6)

hist(dataset$Q7)

hist(dataset$Q8)

hist(dataset$Q9)

hist(dataset$Q10)

Now distibution is fine

Parallel analysis

fa.parallel(dataset, fa="both", n.iter=100) 

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  2  and the number of components =  1

Parallel analysis indicates number of factors=2 and number of components = 1. While optimal number of factors according to plot is 1
